In [17]:
def date_time(x):
    try:
        x=dt.datetime.strptime(str(x), '%d-%m-%Y')
    except:
        x=dt.datetime.strptime(str(x),'%m/%d/%Y')
    return x

Moreover, we can see that the variables new cases, total death, and new death have strong relationships with one another.

def plot_df(df, x, y, title="", xlabel='Date', ylabel='Number of total_cases', dpi=100):
    plt.figure(figsize=(15,4), dpi=dpi)
    plt.plot(x, y, color='tab:red')
    plt.gca().set(title=title, xlabel=xlabel, ylabel=ylabel)
    plt.show()

'''The time series plot reveals a consistent upward trend in the rise of new cases in the United States.
We can also see outliers in January 2022, where the number of new cases peaked and then sharply declined in the same month.
This suggests a rapid change in the types of illnesses that are being reported on a daily basis.
We can observe that there is a consistent upward trend in the number of new COVID cases each month, which is seasonal
because it decreases in the months of April and July.'''
